{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.35,0.61,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7130"},{"type":"tags","id":"10375"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21603"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brain contains interconnected structures that coordinate emotional responses and memory formation. These regions have distinct but complementary functions in processing experiences and feelings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brain structures is primarily responsible for linking emotions to memories?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellum","Basal ganglia","Hippocampus","Amygdala","Prefrontal cortex"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamygdala\u003C/strong\u003E serves as the primary neural structure for associating emotional context with experiences and memories. Through extensive connections with memory-forming regions, particularly the hippocampus, it enables the emotional colouring of memories. People with amygdala lesions often retain the ability to form new memories but struggle to process their emotional significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehippocampus\u003C/strong\u003E forms explicit memories and manages spatial information but requires amygdala input for emotional context. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E coordinates movement and balance while contributing to implicit motor learning. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E regulate movement and participate in procedural learning and reward processing. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprefrontal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E enables planning, judgment and emotional regulation through executive control. The amygdala\u0027s connections with these and other brain regions allow it to integrate emotional significance into the overall memory experience. This is particularly important for learning from emotionally charged events and responding appropriately to environmental threats.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The amygdala is essential for associating emotional context with experiences and memories.","Integration between the amygdala and hippocampus enables formation of emotionally-laden memories.","The amygdala mediates emotional responses including fear conditioning and threat detection."],"references":["Raslau FD, Klein AP, Ulmer JL, Mathews V, Mark LP. Memory part 1: overview. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2014 Nov-Dec;35(11):2058-60. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A4059. Epub 2014 Jul 17. PMID: 25034776; PMCID: PMC7965175","\u0160imi\u0107 G, Tkal\u010di\u0107 M, Vuki\u0107 V, Mulc D, \u0160pani\u0107 E, \u0160agud M, Olucha-Bordonau FE, Vuk\u0161i\u0107 M, R Hof P. Understanding Emotions: Origins and Roles of the Amygdala. Biomolecules. 2021 May 31;11(6):823. doi: 10.3390/biom11060823. PMID: 34072960; PMCID: PMC8228195.","Mariani C, Sacco L, Spinnler H, Venneri A. General Knowledge of the World: a standardised assessment. Neurol Sci. 2002 Oct;23(4):161-75. doi: 10.1007/s100720200057. PMID: 12536285","Jawabri KH, Cascella M. Physiology, Explicit Memory. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554551/","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98518"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116525"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical me